<h1 class="hero-h">Start a gym <em style="color:#00C853;font-style:italic;">vs buy an existing one.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">The buy-vs-build decision for aspiring fitness operators. Real cost comparison, what you get with each, the financing dynamics, and how the AI-native operational model changes the math in 2026.</p>
</div></div>

<div style="background:#0A1A0A;border-top:1px solid #1A3A1A;border-bottom:1px solid #1A3A1A;padding:1.25rem 2.5rem;">
<div style="max-width:880px;margin:0 auto;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;gap:1rem;flex-wrap:wrap;font-size:0.78rem;color:#8FAF8F;">
<div>By <a href="/about" style="color:#F0FFF0;text-decoration:none;font-weight:500;">Bill Colbert</a> · <span style="color:#4A6A4A;">Founder, Treetop Growth Strategy</span></div>
<div style="color:#4A6A4A;">Published May 2026 · <a href="/content-library" style="color:#8FAF8F;text-decoration:none;">More from the library</a></div>
</div>
</div>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Quick answer</span><h2 class="h2">The trade-off in one table</h2><div class="table-wrap"><table class="t"><thead><tr><th>Factor</th><th>Start from scratch</th><th>Buy existing</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Upfront capital</td><td>\$80K-\$1.5M+ (typically lower for small format)</td><td>\$200K-\$5M+ (includes goodwill / member base value)</td></tr><tr><td>Time to revenue</td><td>6-12 months</td><td>Day 1</td></tr><tr><td>Member acquisition</td><td>You do it all</td><td>Inherit existing base</td></tr><tr><td>Brand control</td><td>Full</td><td>Constrained by inherited brand</td></tr><tr><td>Tech / systems flexibility</td><td>Build from scratch (advantage in 2026)</td><td>Often inherit legacy systems</td></tr><tr><td>Risk profile</td><td>Higher (concept unproven locally)</td><td>Lower (existing P&amp;L)</td></tr><tr><td>Owner energy required</td><td>Higher early</td><td>Lower early; higher mid-term</td></tr><tr><td>Multiplier you pay</td><td>None</td><td>2-5x annual EBITDA typically</td></tr></tbody></table></div></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">When starting from scratch makes sense</span><h2 class="h2">Five scenarios that favor building</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>You have an existing client base / coach reputation.</strong> Trainer-to-owner transitions are uniquely well-suited to launching new.</li><li><strong>You want full brand and operational control.</strong> Build the concept you actually want.</li><li><strong>You want to build agentic-from-day-one operations.</strong> Buying an existing gym means inheriting legacy software stacks and staff models that may resist AI-native operational changes.</li><li><strong>Your market has no quality acquisition targets.</strong> Sometimes there's nothing worth buying in your geography.</li><li><strong>Capital is tighter than time.</strong> Building lean takes less capital than buying.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">When buying existing makes sense</span><h2 class="h2">Five scenarios that favor acquiring</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>You want revenue from day one.</strong> The biggest reason to buy.</li><li><strong>You're risk-averse on concept-market fit.</strong> Existing P&amp;L is proven (review carefully).</li><li><strong>You're acquiring as part of a multi-unit roll-up.</strong> Buying multiple existing locations + applying operational excellence (including AI-native upgrades) is a strong consolidation play.</li><li><strong>The seller is motivated and the price reflects it.</strong> Distress sales sometimes offer real value.</li><li><strong>You can credibly run / improve the operation.</strong> Don't buy what you can't operate.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">The AI-native angle that changes 2026 math</span><h2 class="h2">Why this matters more now</h2><p class="body">In 2025-2026, the operational gap between AI-native gym operations and legacy operations widened dramatically. Implications for the buy-vs-build decision:</p><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Acquiring an existing gym often means acquiring its legacy operational debt.</strong> Old CRM, manual lead-nurture workflows, multi-person front-desk staff models. Upgrading to AI-native operations post-acquisition is often a 12-18 month project on its own.</li><li><strong>Starting fresh lets you build agentic from day one.</strong> An AI-native new gym deployment with <a href="https://fitagentic.ai" style="color:#00C853;">fitagentic.ai</a> from the lease signing onward typically operates at 30-50% lower staffing overhead than the equivalent legacy operation.</li><li><strong>For roll-up acquirers,</strong> the playbook is now: acquire existing operations at reasonable multiples, then aggressively apply AI-native operational upgrades — that's where the post-acquisition value creation happens.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Cost comparison: small boutique studio</span><h2 class="h2">Concrete example</h2><h3 class="h3">Start from scratch</h3><ul class="ul"><li>Facility, equipment, licensing, software, marketing, working capital: \$120K-\$280K</li><li>Time to revenue: 6-9 months</li><li>Member acquisition: do it yourself</li><li>Year-1 owner take-home: typically minimal to modest</li></ul><h3 class="h3">Buy existing comparable studio</h3><ul class="ul"><li>Purchase price at typical 2-3x EBITDA multiple: \$200K-\$600K depending on size and profitability</li><li>Down payment (typically 20-30%): \$50K-\$180K</li><li>SBA financing on the rest: ~10-year amortization</li><li>Time to revenue: day 1</li><li>Year-1 owner take-home: depends entirely on the acquired business's existing P&amp;L</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Diligence checklist for buyers</span><h2 class="h2">What to verify before signing</h2><ul class="ul"><li>Real member count (vs claimed) — pull access logs not member lists</li><li>Real churn rate (last 12 months)</li><li>Member-to-revenue concentration (is one founding member 30% of revenue?)</li><li>Lease terms and remaining duration</li><li>Equipment age and condition (depreciation reality)</li><li>Existing software contracts (assignment terms)</li><li>Staff retention if key staff are part of the value</li><li>Reason for sale (real reason — not the stated reason)</li><li>Pending or threatened litigation</li><li>Recent online reviews and reputation</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Companion tools</span><h2 class="h2">Build your decision</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong><a href="/cost-to-start-a-gym" style="color:#00C853;">Cost to Start a Gym (full guide)</a></strong></li><li><strong><a href="/gym-startup-cost-calculator" style="color:#00C853;">Gym Startup Cost Calculator</a></strong></li><li><strong><a href="/ai-for-multi-unit-fitness-operators-playbook" style="color:#00C853;">AI for Multi-Unit Fitness Operators Playbook</a></strong> — relevant for roll-up acquirers.</li></ul></div></section>

